tags.name: Availability
tags.description:
An endpoint for clients to determine the availability of symbol service for the current VSTS account.

This controller does not sit behind any feature flag.

The controller returns 200 if the service is available. Any other codes indicate that the service is not available.
For now, only 404 is used explicitly, but the client may also receive 500 if an internal error arises. In the future
we may add 402 to indicate a license issue.

Visual Studio IDE calls this when connecting to symbol server, but it doesn't use SymbolHttpClient due to restrictions
on binplacing micro-service DLLs inside Team Explorer package.

Trace Format: Artifact Services: 57, Symbol Service: 3, SymbolAvailabilityController: 6 -> 5736MM0 for all Exception traces

tags.name: Symsrv

The endpoint to query debug entries using a "client key". This is intended to be called by a client that implements 
Microsoft's symbol protocol (symsrv).

DebugEntry.description: A dual-purpose data object, the debug entry is used by the client to publish the symbol file (with file's blob identifier, which can be calculated from VSTS hashing algorithm) or query the file (with a client key). Since the symbol server tries to return a matched symbol file with the richest information level, it may not always point to the same symbol file for different queries with same client key.

blobDetails.description: Details of the blob formatted to be deserialized for symbol service.

blobIdentifier.description: A blob identifier of the symbol file to upload to this debug entry. This property is mostly used during creation of debug entry (a.k.a. symbol publishing) to allow the server to query the existence of the blob.

blobUri.description: The URI to get the symbol file. Provided by the server, the URI contains authentication information and is readily accessible by plain HTTP GET request. The client is recommended to retrieve the file as soon as it can since the URI will expire in a short period.

clientKey.description: A key the client (debugger, for example) uses to find the debug entry. Note it is not unique for each different symbol file as it does not distinguish between those which only differ by information level.

domainId.description: The Domain Id where this debugEntry lives. This property should not be null.

informationLevel.description: The information level this debug entry contains.

values.description: If set, the .pdb file contains no debug information.
If set, the .pdb file contains debug information which is binary.
If set, the .pdb file contains public symbols.
If set, the .pdb file contains trace format.
If set, the .pdb file contains type information.
If set, the .pdb file contains line number information.
If set, the .pdb file contains symbol information.
If set, the .pdb file contains public symbols and has type, line number and symbol information.
If set, the .pdb file supports the source server.

requestId.description: The identifier of symbol request to which this debug entry belongs.

size.description: The size for the debug entry.

values.description: The status of this debug entry is undefined or irrelevant in the current context.
The debug entry is created and read to use.
The symbol file for the requested debug entry is missing.

DebugEntryCreateBatch.description: A batch of debug entry to create.

createBehavior.description: Defines what to do when a debug entry in the batch already exists.

values.description: Throw exceptions at server end. This will translate to 409 (Conflict) HTTP status code.
Do not add this debug entry. The rest of the batch, if any, is not affected.

proofNodes.description: Serialized Proof nodes, used to verify uploads on server side for Chunk Dedup DebugEntry

JsonBlobBlockHash.description: BlobBlock hash formatted to be deserialized for symbol service.

JsonBlobIdentifierWithBlocks.description: BlobIdentifier with block hashes formatted to be deserialzied for symbol service.

domainId.description: The Domain Id where this request lives. This property should not be null.

expirationDate.description: An optional expiration date for the request. The request will become inaccessible and get deleted after the date, regardless of its status.  On an HTTP POST, if expiration date is null/missing, the server will assign a default expiration data (30 days unless overwridden in the registry at the account level). On PATCH, if expiration date is null/missing, the behavior is to not change whatever the request's current expiration date is.

isChunked.description: Indicates if request should be chunk dedup
